        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </problem>
</section>





<section xml:id="LimitAsPrimary">
  <title>The Limit as a Primary Tool</title>
  <p>
    As you saw in the <xref ref="SeqRealNum"
    text="custom">previous section</xref> the formal definition of
    the convergence of a sequence is meant to capture rigorously
    our intuitive understanding of convergence.  However, the
    definition itself is an unwieldy tool. If only there were some
    way to be rigorous without having to run back to the
    definition each time.  Fortunately, there is a way.  If we can
    use the definition to prove some general rules about limits
    then we could use these rules whenever they apply and be
    assured that everything was still rigorous.  A number of these
    should look familiar from Calculus.
      </p>

      <problem xml:id="PROBLEMLimConst">
        <title>Limit of a Constant Sequence is the Constant</title>

        <idx><h>limit</h><h>of a constant sequence</h></idx>
        <idx><h>sequences</h><h>constant sequences</h></idx>

        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\left(c\right)_{n=1}^\infty=(c,c,c,\ldots)</m> be a
            constant sequence.  Show that
            <m>\limitt{n}{\infty}{c}=c</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </problem>

      <p>
        In proving the familiar limit theorems,
        the following will be a very useful tool.
      </p>

      <lemma xml:id="Tri-RevTri-Ineq">
        <idx><h>Triangle Inequalities</h></idx>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <dl>
              <li xml:id="TriangleIneq">  <title>Triangle Inequality:</title>
              <idx><h>Triangle Inequalities</h><h>Triangle Inequality</h></idx>
              <p>
                Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be real numbers.
                Then
                <me>
                  \abs{a+b}\leq \abs{a}+\abs{b}
                  </me>.
              </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="InvTriangleIneq"> <title>Reverse Triangle Inequality:</title>
              <idx><h>Triangle Inequalities</h><h>Reverse Triangle Inequalitiy</h></idx>
              <p>
                Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be real numbers.
                Then
                <me>
                  \abs{a}-\abs{b}\leq\abs{a-b}
                </me>
              </p>
              </li>
            </dl>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>




      <problem xml:id="Tri-RevTri-Ineq_prob">
      
        <idx><h>Triangle Inequalities</h><h>Triangle Inequality</h></idx>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Prove <xref ref="Tri-RevTri-Ineq"></xref>. 
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              For the Reverse Triangle Inequality,
              consider <m>\abs{a}=\abs{a-b+b}</m>.
            </p>
          </hint>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show <m>\Big||a|-|b|\Big|\leq|a-b|</m>. 
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              You want to show that 
              <me>|a|-|b|\leq|a-b|</me> and that <me>-\left(|a|-|b|\right)\leq|a-b|</me>.
            </p>
          </hint>

        </task>
      </problem>

      <theorem xml:id="thm_SumOfSequences">
        <title>Limit of a Sum of Sequences is the Sum of the Limits</title>

        <idx><h>limit</h><h> of a sum of sequences</h></idx>

        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>\limitt{n}{\infty}{a_n}=a</m> and
            <m>\limitt{n}{\infty}{b_n}=b</m>,
            then <me>\limit{n}{\infty}{\left(a_n+b_n\right)}=a+b</me>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>

      <p>
        We will often state this theorem informally as <q>the limit of
        a sum is the sum of the limits.</q> However, to be absolutely
        precise, what it says is that if we already know that two
        sequences converge, then the sequence formed by summing their
        corresponding terms  will also converge and
        in fact, it will converge to the sum of those individual limits.
      </p>
      <p>
      </p>

      <problem>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <idx><h>sequences</h><h>termwise sums of</h></idx>
            Prove <xref ref="thm_SumOfSequences"></xref>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We<rsq/>ll provide the scrapwork and leave the formal
            write<ndash/>up to you. Be sure you justify every
            step. Also, note the role of the <xref ref="Tri-RevTri-Ineq" text="custom">triangle inequality</xref> in
            the proof.
          </p>

          <p>
            <term>SCRAPWORK:</term>
          </p>
          <p>
            If we let <m>\eps>0</m>, then we want to find <m>N</m>
            such that if <m>n>N</m>, then
            <m>\big|\left(a_n+b_n\right)-\left(a+b\right)\big|\lt
            \eps</m>.  Since we know that
            <m>\limit{n}{\infty}{a_n}=a</m> and
            <m>\limit{n}{\infty}{b_n}=b</m>, we can make
            <m>\big|a_n-a\big|</m> and <m>\big|b_n-b\big|</m> as small
            as we wish, provided we make <m>n</m> large enough.
            Let<rsq/>s go back to what we want, to see if we can close
            the gap between what we know and what we want.  We know,
            by the triangle inequality, that
            <me>
              \left|\left(a_n+b_n\right)-\left(a+b\right)\right|=\left|\left(a_n-a\right)+\left(b_n-b\right)\right|\leq\left|a_n-a\right|+\left|b_n-b\right|
              </me>.
              To make this whole thing less than <m>\eps</m>,
              it makes sense to make each part less than <m>\frac{\eps}{2}</m>.
              
          </p>
          <p>
            Fortunately, we can do that as the definitions of 
            <m>\limit{n}{\infty}{a_n}=a</m> and <m>\limit{n}{\infty}{b_n}=b</m> allow us to make
            <m>\abs{a_n-a}</m> and <m>\abs{b_n-b}</m> arbitrarily small.
          </p>
          <p>
            Specifically, since <m>\limit{n}{\infty}{a_n}=a</m>, there
            exists an <m>N_1</m> such that if <m>n>N_1</m> then
            <m>\abs{a_n-a}\lt \frac{\eps}{2}</m>.  Also since
            <m>\limit{n}{\infty}{b_n}=b</m>, there exists an <m>N_2</m>
            such that if <m>n>N_2</m> then <m>\abs{b_n-b}\lt
            \frac{\eps}{2}</m>.  Since we want both of these to occur,
            it makes sense to let
            <m>N=</m>max<m>\left(N_1,N_2\right)</m>.  This should be the
            <m>N</m> that we seek.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <!-- <hint> -->
        <!--   <title>SCRAPWORK</title> -->

        <!--   <p> -->
        <!--     <term>SCRAPWORK:</term> -->
        <!--   </p> -->
